.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/references/agent-improvement/score_dimensions.md:225:| `scripts/agent-improvement/generate-profile.cjs` | Dynamic profile generation |
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/references/agent-improvement/score_dimensions.md:226:| `scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs` | Integration surface discovery |
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:1:deep-agent-improvement gained a first-class model-benchmark mode and, on top of it, became a genuine two-lane skill end to end: Lane A (improve an agent file) and Lane B (benchmark a model or prompt framework) are now co-equal at the command, doc, agent, and on-disk layers. The capability was built from a designed mode-selector + pluggable seams, then hardened by two independent deep-review -> remediation cycles (gpt-5.5 and Opus 4.8) before Lane B shipped.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:3:> Spec parent: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode` (covers the 121 program across both arcs — Build 001-007 and Two-lane 008-018; consolidated here by the 019 doc closeout).
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:14:- **`loop-host.cjs` gained a mode-switch entry point.** It now dispatches between `agent-improvement` (the existing path, untouched) and `--mode=model-benchmark`, so the same loop shape can drive either an agent definition or a model/prompt benchmark.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:15:- **New `dispatch-model.cjs` generic dispatcher** runs a model against fixtures under prompt-framework variants — the Lane B equivalent of dispatching a Claude agent, but for arbitrary models across the 5 executors.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:17:- **Mode-aware state records:** loop state now carries a `mode` field so a benchmark run reaches `benchmark-complete` and is distinguishable from agent-improvement runs in the journal and registry.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:18:- **TST-1 byte-identity gate:** the agent-improvement branch is held byte-identical through every build and reorg, so the existing lane provably never regresses.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:28:- **Remediated the 3 unique confirmed P1 defects** (phase 004), each with a regression test: the dispatcher dropped the requested working directory for 4 of 5 executors (cwd now propagates to `spawnSync` for all 5), the D3 path guard misclassified sibling-prefix paths (now a separator-bounded prefix guard), acceptance criteria ran un-gated shell commands (now a criteria-exec gate, default ON with a documented opt-out), and the D4 grader accepted unbounded model scores (now clamped to `[0,1]`).
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:29:- **Closed the actionable P2 advisories** in the same pass: Atomics-based backoff replacing the busy-wait, a grader-cache raw-input gate, dependency-injected `fs` in `dispute.cjs` (removing a global monkey-patch), a deterministic-scoring regression test, delta-units documentation, and a reconciled REQ-004 `--cwd` wording. The two non-defects (intended deferral, dedup artifact) were recorded as no-change with rationale.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:33:- **Deep-loop init no longer creates empty `{mode}_archive` directories.** All 4 deep-loop restart branches now archive lazily and guarded, with regression tests, and pre-existing empty archive dirs were swept.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:39:- **`/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` now resolves a use-case lane.** When an agent path is supplied it auto-resolves to Lane A and runs exactly as before (CMD-1 behavioral identity), so existing invocations are untouched. A `--lane=model-benchmark` flag or a `--profile` argument routes to Lane B, and a lane question appears only when the lane is genuinely ambiguous.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:41:- **Advisor registration:** a `deep-model-benchmark` alias group plus bounded command-level disambiguation so benchmark phrasing routes to the new command rather than the Lane A one.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:42:- **Latent fix:** `loop-host.cjs` never forwarded `--scorer` and `--grader` to `run-benchmark.cjs`, so selecting `5dim` or a `mock`/`llm` grader through any command path silently fell back to `pattern`/`noop` while the report disagreed with the journal. Both flags are now forwarded in the model-benchmark branch only, with a regression test. The agent-improvement branch is byte-identical so TST-1 stays green.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:46:- **The skill doc presents Lane A and Lane B as parallel sections** instead of modes 1 to 3 plus a trailing Mode 4. A WHEN TO USE two-lane table was added, and the smart router gained a `MODEL_BENCHMARK` intent at weight 5 with a matching RESOURCE_MAP entry. DQI stayed in the excellent band at 97.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:50:- **`references/` and `assets/` are now organized by lane** (`agent-improvement/`, `model-benchmark/`, `shared/`) rather than by function. This supersedes the v1.8.0.0 function grouping (scoring, promotion-gates, integration, workflow), which was an intermediate step. Every literal was repointed: SKILL.md RESOURCE_MAP, DEFAULT_RESOURCE, RUNTIME_ASSETS, both lanes of command YAMLs, both command docs, README, graph-metadata, scripts, the feature catalog and playbook, and the benchmark profile's internal fixtureDir.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:54:- **The `@deep-agent-improvement` awareness note went from "Mode awareness" to "Lane awareness"** across all 4 runtime mirrors, byte-identical (mirror-drift 0). The note makes clear there is one agent and Lane B dispatches models through `dispatch-model.cjs`, never a second Claude agent.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:59:- **F-P2-5 closed:** `reduce-state.cjs` now surfaces the `mode` metadata it already recorded. The registry carries per-profile and global `modes`, and the dashboard prints a "Lane (mode) mix" line in the global summary and each profile section. This is display only, routing is untouched, and a missing mode counts as agent-improvement so legacy ledgers still total. A new regression test covers it.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:63:- **The 16 scripts moved into `scripts/{agent-improvement,model-benchmark,shared}/`** (with `scorer/` under model-benchmark), while `lib/` and `tests/` stay at the scripts root. `loop-host.planInvocation()` was kept byte-identical and a new `resolveScriptPath()` helper does lane resolution at spawn time, so TST-1 holds. `dispatch-model.cjs` path joins were re-depthed (its config load is positively asserted to resolve to a real file, closing a silent-fallback risk). All references were rewritten, including the vitest path literals (13 suites at that phase).
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:74:- **Remediated the Opus findings (phase 018):** the 4 P1 + 13 P2 were closed with one disposition each — including a materializer fixture-id guard, a bundle-gate criteria-exec gate, removal of dead Mode-4 anchors, and an executable Lane B benchmark-mode promotion path matched to its documented truth, with regression tests.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:80:This release covers the entire 121 program. Arc 1 designed (001), deep-researched (002), built (003), and hardened (007 review -> 004 remediation) the model-benchmark mode, then added the opt-in 5-dim scorer + docs (005) and a maintenance fix (006). Arc 2 elevated model-benchmark from a "Mode 4" bolt-on to a lane co-equal with agent-improvement across command (008), SKILL.md (009), references/assets (010), the agent note (011), catalog/playbook/advisor (012), and scripts (013), then hardened it with two independent deep-review -> remediation cycles — gpt-5.5 (014 -> 015) and Opus 4.8 (017 -> 018) — plus per-subfolder code READMEs (016). The tri-model hardening review of Arc 1 was originally scaffolded as separate packet 122 and folded into 121 as phase 007 on 2026-05-29; that is why remediation phase 004 carries a lower number than the review it remediates (007). Each phase ran as an agentic workflow with an independent verification pass.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:85:- Both lanes smoke end to end: agent-improvement scores a candidate, model-benchmark reaches `benchmark-complete` with `pattern` and `5dim`.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:86:- Advisor routes benchmark phrasing to `deep-model-benchmark` and agent phrasing to agent-improvement.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:88:- Both deep-review cycles returned CONDITIONAL and were fully remediated: gpt-5.5 (1 P0 + 16 P1 + 16 P2) and Opus 4.8 (4 P1 + 13 P2), with regression tests per fix.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:93:No migration required for callers of `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` with an agent path, which behave exactly as before. New work that benchmarks a model or prompt framework should use `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` or pass `--lane=model-benchmark`; opt into the 5-dim rubric with `--scorer=5dim` (default stays `pattern`). Internal scripts moved into lane subdirs, so any external caller hardcoding `scripts/<name>.cjs` should update to `scripts/<lane>/<name>.cjs`.
