.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:1:# Iteration 003 — Lane C "skill-benchmark": activation scoring across TWO routers (RQ3) + non-circular fixture authoring (RQ4)
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:4:> Web note: `WebSearch`/`WebFetch` remained permission-gated in this background context (not retried, consistent with iters 001–002). The few external concepts referenced (train/test holdout, metamorphic testing, data-leakage) are established and flagged `[web-unverified]`; the load-bearing evidence this iteration is all **first-hand from repo files**, especially the advisor's live scorer + validation baselines. Builds on iter-001 (D1–D5 dimensions) and iter-002 (hint-free harness, contamination linter, two-author separation).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:10:**RQ3** — Should activation accuracy be scored against the **skill-advisor**, the **in-`SKILL.md` smart router**, or **both as separate sub-scores**? What does "properly utilized" mean operationally?
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:12:**RQ4** — Scenario/fixture authoring: hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers — how to get realistic coverage while **avoiding circularity** (scoring a skill against scenarios derived from itself).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:20:1. Re-read the target skill `deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md` (full) — pinned the in-skill router's `INTENT_SIGNALS`/`RESOURCE_MAP`, its literal-substring `score_intents`, and the frontmatter `triggers:` block, to compare the two routing surfaces directly.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:21:2. Re-read `system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md` (full) — confirmed the advisor is a *separate* routing layer (`advisor_recommend` over all skills) with its own substring `score_intents` and an explicit confidence threshold for invocation.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:22:3. **Read `system-skill-advisor/references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md` (full, NEW this iteration)** — captured the real advisor scorer: **5 weighted lanes** (explicit_author 0.42, lexical 0.28, graph_causal 0.13, derived_generated 0.12, semantic_shadow 0.05), the 16 confidence-calibration constants, the derived-dominant 0.72 confidence ceiling, and ambiguity-cluster detection at a 0.05 margin.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:23:4. **Read `system-skill-advisor/references/scoring/validation_baselines.md` (full, NEW this iteration)** — captured `advisor_validate`'s existing routing-accuracy harness: **corpus top-1 80.5%**, **holdout top-1 77.5%**, UNKNOWN count, parity/safety/latency slices, and the explicit corpus-vs-holdout overfit signal. This is the repo's own, already-shipped answer to RQ4 circularity.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:24:5. Re-read prior opus iterations 001 and 002 and the phase spec — anchored RQ3/RQ4 against D1 (routing/activation), iter-002's contamination linter (F7) and two-author separation, and iter-001's auto-derived-fixture proposal (F9), to extend rather than repeat them.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:32:There are two routers in scope and they operate at different altitudes on different inputs:
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:34:- **Inter-skill (the skill-advisor)** decides *which skill, among all skills*, should handle a prompt. Entry: `advisor_recommend` on `mk_skill_advisor`; "top recommendation above confidence threshold -> invoke that skill." [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:61-72]
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:35:- **Intra-skill (the in-`SKILL.md` smart router)** runs *after* a skill is already selected and decides *which `references/`+`assets/` to load within it*, via `INTENT_SIGNALS`→`RESOURCE_MAP`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-138,183-213]
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:38:- Advisor miss → fix frontmatter `triggers`/`keywords`/`intent_signals`, derived metadata, skill-graph edges, or lane weights.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:39:- In-skill-router miss → fix `INTENT_SIGNALS` keywords or `RESOURCE_MAP` entries.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:45:The advisor is **not** a keyword matcher — it is a five-lane weighted scorer: explicit_author 0.42, lexical 0.28, graph_causal 0.13, derived_generated 0.12, semantic_shadow 0.05 (shadow-only). [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md:46-52] A Lane C activation check that only greps frontmatter substrings (the temptation, since the in-skill router *is* substring-based) would mis-measure the advisor entirely — it would ignore graph edges, embeddings, and curated boosts.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:47:Decisively, **the routing-accuracy harness Lane C's inter-skill sub-score needs already exists**: `advisor_validate` reports full-corpus **top-1 = 80.5%** and held-out **top-1 = 77.5%**, plus `telemetry.unknownCount` (≤10), parity, safety, and latency slices. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/scoring/validation_baselines.md:43-57,75-87] **Recommendation:** Lane C's inter-skill activation sub-score = call `advisor_recommend` per fixture for the per-skill rank/confidence, and reuse the `advisor_validate` `perSkill[]` slice for the corpus/holdout top-1. This makes the inter-skill score consistent with the production router and gives Lane C a free, calibrated baseline instead of a parallel definition of "routed correctly."
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:53:- **Derived-dominant confidence ceiling = 0.72, below the 0.8 invoke bar.** Confidence is pinned to 0.72 when the derived lane dominates and `directScore < 0.2`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md:106,117] But Gate 2 requires **confidence ≥ 0.8 to MUST-invoke a skill** [SOURCE: project CLAUDE.md §2 Gate 2], and the scorer's `taskIntentFloor`/`directScoreFloor` are both 0.82 [SOURCE: advisor_scorer.md:118-119]. So a skill reachable *only* through derived/generated triggers (no curated `explicit_author` boost, weak `lexical` coverage) is **structurally capped below the invocation threshold** — it can never be auto-invoked no matter how relevant. Remediation is specific: add an `explicit_author` TOKEN/PHRASE boost or strengthen `lexical` keywords so `directScore` clears 0.2. Lane C should flag any under-test skill whose typical winning lane is `derived_generated`.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:54:- **Ambiguity clusters are the measurable form of "near-neighbor confusion" (iter-001 F2).** The scorer unions a score-gap and confidence-gap test at a **0.05 margin** to flag ambiguity. [SOURCE: advisor_scorer.md:127,137] The live brief this very session — `ambiguous: sk-code 0.95/0.16 vs deep-research 0.93/0.16` [SOURCE: UserPromptSubmit hook context, this session] — is exactly such a cluster (0.02 score gap < 0.05). Lane C's inter-skill sub-score should report **ambiguity-cluster rate** for the skill-under-test (how often it lands in a sub-0.05 tie with a sibling) as a distinct, remediable metric: collision → disambiguating keyword/boost or a skill-graph `siblings`/`conflicts_with` edge.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:60:Synthesizing iter-001 D1–D5 + iter-002 Mode A/B + this iteration's two-layer split, "properly utilized" means **all** of the following hold for an in-scope task, in order:
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:62:1. **Reachable** (static gate, iter-001 D5): the in-skill router *can* load the right reference and the skill's metadata *can* route — no orphan ref, no dead `RESOURCE_MAP` key. [SOURCE: opus/iterations/iteration-001.md:102-114]
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:64:3. **Routed — intra-skill** (F1): for the paraphrased prompt, the in-`SKILL.md` router's loaded set contains the gold reference (iter-002 Mode A router-replay, deterministic). [SOURCE: opus/iterations/iteration-002.md:26-30]
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:66:5. **Useful — causal** (iter-001 D4): skill-on beats skill-off on the same fixture (ablation). [SOURCE: opus/iterations/iteration-001.md:83-100]
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:68:A skill that passes 1–2 but fails 3 is *invoked but mis-routed internally*; passes 1–3 but fails 4 is *routable but not signposted inline*; passes 1–4 but fails 5 is *used but not earning its context cost → retire/merge*. The conjunction is the definition; the **first failing stage is the finding**. This is what makes Lane C remediable rather than a vanity score.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:72:The two routers key on *different strings for the same concept*, so a prompt can pass inter-skill and fail intra-skill:
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:74:- Frontmatter trigger (seen by the advisor's derived/lexical lanes): **`dynamic profiling`**. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:12]
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:75:- In-skill `INTENT_SIGNALS["INTEGRATION_SCAN"]` keyword (seen by the in-skill router): **`dynamic profile`**. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:119]
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:77:The in-skill router matches by literal substring: `if keyword in text`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:168-172] The string `"dynamic profile"` is **not** a substring of `"dynamic profiling"` (`…profil` + `ing`, never `…profile`). So a user prompt "do dynamic profiling on this agent" matches the advisor's frontmatter trigger (inter-skill: PASS) but scores **zero** on `INTEGRATION_SCAN` in the in-skill router, falling back to the `QUICK_REFERENCE` default and **failing to load `references/agent-improvement/integration_scanning.md`** (intra-skill: MISS). [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:124-133,176-181] This is a concrete, repo-verified instance of the inter-pass/intra-fail split — exactly the case a single fused activation score would hide, and exactly the kind of one-line remediation (align the keyword) Lane C exists to surface. (A separate, lower-confidence note: the target skill's frontmatter key is `triggers:` while the advisor reference and `system-skill-advisor` use `trigger_phrases:` — Lane C's connectivity gate should verify the under-test skill's frontmatter key is one the advisor actually projects into `derivedTriggers`; I could not confirm the projection without reading scorer source. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:6 vs .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:6])
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:79:### F6 — RQ4: pure generated-from-self fixtures are MATHEMATICALLY circular against these routers — a guaranteed false pass
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:81:Both routers are literal-substring matchers (in-skill: `if keyword in text` [SOURCE: deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:168-172]; advisor lexical/derived lanes do token matching over the same metadata [SOURCE: advisor_scorer.md:62-66,94-98]). If a fixture prompt is generated by lifting a `trigger`/`INTENT_SIGNALS` string verbatim, then scored on whether routing fires, you are evaluating `X ⊆ X` — a tautological pass that measures keyword echo, not discovery. iter-002 F5 already proved this is a "guaranteed false pass." [SOURCE: opus/iterations/iteration-002.md:46-60] Therefore generated-from-self prompts are usable for **coverage/breadth** but are **invalid as scored discovery fixtures unless transformed and decontaminated**.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:83:### F7 — RQ4 answer: a THREE-TIER fixture taxonomy; the repo's own corpus-vs-holdout split is the proven non-circular pattern to copy
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:85:The advisor team already solved "don't measure on what you tuned on": the **corpus** slice (top-1 80.5%) is the tuned-on set; the **holdout** slice (top-1 77.5%) is "a curated subset reserved for measuring generalization … unseen during weight tuning," and a holdout drop > 1pp is "a stronger regression signal than the corpus slice because holdout is unseen." [SOURCE: validation_baselines.md:43-57,98-103] Lane C should mirror this exactly with three tiers:
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:89:| **T1 generated-from-self** | auto-derived from `WHEN TO USE`/`triggers`/`RESOURCE_MAP` (iter-001 F9) [SOURCE: opus/iterations/iteration-001.md:139-144], then **paraphrased + contamination-linted** (F8) | breadth/coverage; cheap; regenerable after rename | circular UNLESS decontaminated |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:90:| **T2 hand-authored holdout** | realistic task scenarios written from the *task domain*, never from the skill's metadata; author blind to `INTENT_SIGNALS`/`RESOURCE_MAP` | generalization truth; the honesty anchor | non-circular by construction |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:91:| **T3 adversarial near-neighbor / decoy / negative** | sibling-skill paraphrases (iter-001 OQ), decoy fixtures whose gold key belongs to a *different* skill (iter-002 F8), and "When NOT to Use" negatives [SOURCE: deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:66-72] | stresses D1 precision + abstention | non-circular |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:97:To make T1 usable rather than tautological, generate by **semantics-preserving transformation** then verify routing **invariance** — the metamorphic-testing pattern [SOURCE: metamorphic testing, general technique `[web-unverified]`]: take the trigger *intent*, paraphrase it into natural task language that contains **none** of the router's literal keyword strings, and assert the skill still routes. Two mandatory guards, both already designed in iter-002:
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:99:- **Contamination linter as admission gate** — reject any T1 prompt containing the skill name, any skill-relative path, or any `triggers`/`keywords`/`intent_signals` substring, using the routers' own substring logic so "decontaminated" is decided by the same mechanism that would otherwise be gamed. [SOURCE: opus/iterations/iteration-002.md:65-66]
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:100:- **Two-author separation** — the gold key is derived mechanically from `RESOURCE_MAP` by the scorer side; the decontaminated prompt is authored from a paraphrased task brief by a different side, so the prompt author cannot unconsciously seed the answer. [SOURCE: opus/iterations/iteration-002.md:65-66] This is the operational guarantee that "generated from the skill" ≠ "scored against itself."
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:104:"Realistic coverage" (RQ4) needs two explicit metrics so the generated tier is neither thin nor inflated:
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:106:- **Intent/resource coverage** — assert ≥1 admitted fixture per `INTENT_SIGNALS` key AND ≥1 per `RESOURCE_MAP` target file, plus ≥1 negative per "When NOT to Use" bullet. Uncovered keys/refs are themselves findings (an intent no realistic prompt can trigger may be a dead key — links iter-001 D5). [SOURCE: deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-133,66-72]
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:107:- **Fixture dedup via signature** — to stop generation piling near-identical paraphrases, reuse the skill's own `mutation-coverage.cjs` signature pattern (`sha256(dimension∥type∥section∥normalizedBody64)`, whitespace-collapsed/lowercased) adapted to fixtures, so duplicates are skipped the same way duplicate mutations are. [SOURCE: deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:372-393] This gives "coverage" a denominator instead of a vibe.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:113:1. **Emit two activation sub-scores** — `activation.interSkill` (advisor) and `activation.intraSkill` (in-`SKILL.md` router) — never a single fused number (F1, F5).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:114:2. **Build the inter-skill sub-score on the live advisor**: call `advisor_recommend` per fixture and reuse `advisor_validate` corpus/holdout `perSkill[]`; do not re-implement keyword matching, which would ignore 4 of the advisor's 5 lanes (F2).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:116:4. **Define "properly utilized" as the five-stage conjunction** (reachable→activated→routed→discovered→useful) and report the *first failing stage* as the finding (F4).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:117:5. **Adopt the three-tier fixture taxonomy** (generated-decontaminated / hand-authored holdout / adversarial), and **publish the T1↔T2 gap as the circularity meter**, copying the advisor's corpus↔holdout pattern (F6, F7).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:119:7. **Measure coverage (per-intent, per-resource, per-negative) and dedup fixtures via the mutation-coverage signature pattern** so the generated tier is provably broad and not padded (F9).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:128:- **Decontamination of unavoidable common-word triggers:** "benchmark", "integration", "rollback" are both router keywords and ordinary task words; an IDF/specificity weighting (carried over from iter-002 OQ) may be needed so the linter doesn't reject every natural T1 prompt (F8).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:129:- **Cross-skill activation (the routing layer itself):** F3's sk-code/deep-research tie suggests Lane C may also need a *whole-skill-set confusion matrix* (not just per-skill), reusing `advisor_validate`'s corpus slice — is that in Lane C's charter or the advisor's? (links iter-001 OQ)
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/opus/iterations/iteration-003.md:130:- **Mode A↔Mode B agreement for the intra-skill score:** how often does deterministic router-replay (stage 3) agree with the live behavioral open (stage 4)? If high, stage 4 can be sampled rarely (carried from iter-002 OQ).
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:3:description: "Test fixtures for advisor scorer including intent prompt corpora for routing accuracy tests and skill embedding seeding utilities for lane weight sweep experiments."
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:7:  - "lane weight sweep fixtures"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:12:> Test fixture folder providing intent prompt corpora and skill embedding seeding utilities for advisor scorer accuracy experiments.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:18:`tests/scorer/fixtures/` provides test data and utilities for the advisor scorer system. It contains two intent prompt corpora for measuring routing accuracy and an embedding seeding module for lane weight sweep experiments.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:22:- Three TypeScript files provide the full fixture surface. No subdirectories exist beyond the `.embeddings-cache/` data directory.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:24:- `harder-intent-prompt-corpus.ts` exports `HARDER_INTENT_PROMPT_CORPUS`, a readonly array of prompts designed to test lexical mis-routing edge cases. Each entry uses the `lexical-mis-route` category and includes a `reason` field documenting the mis-route hypothesis.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:25:- `seed-skill-embeddings.ts` exports `seedSkillEmbeddings`, an async function that generates and caches skill description vectors. Cache entries are keyed by `sha256(description).slice(0, 16)` concatenated with the provider model ID. The cache file lives at `fixtures/.embeddings-cache/skill-embeddings.json`. The function treats provider creation or embedding failures as environment skips rather than errors and returns `skipped: true` when the embedding provider is unavailable.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:27:- One test file consumes all fixtures: `lane-weight-sweep.vitest.ts` in the parent scorer directory.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:37:| `harder-intent-prompt-corpus.ts` | Exports `HARDER_INTENT_PROMPT_CORPUS` for lexical mis-route testing and the `HarderIntentEntry` interface. |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:49:| `HarderIntentEntry` | interface | Interface for harder intent prompt entries with lexical mis-route categorization. |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/scorer/fixtures/README.md:72:- [Lifecycle Fixtures](../../fixtures/lifecycle/README.md)
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:1:Initial release of `deep-agent-improvement` -- an evaluator-first skill for bounded agent improvement with 5-dimension integration-aware scoring, dynamic profiling, deterministic benchmarks, and guarded promotion. The skill evaluates any agent across its full system integration surface rather than just checking keyword presence in the markdown file. Developed across 8 phases under spec folder `041-sk-recursive-agent-loop`, originally as `sk-recursive-agent` and renamed in Phase 008. The goal is to make the workflow easier to follow and easier to trust.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:11:The skill writes candidates to packet-local runtime areas instead of editing main agent files directly. Each candidate is scored independently by a deterministic evaluator, benchmarked against target-specific fixture sets, and tracked in an append-only JSONL ledger. Promotion to the main target requires passing all evidence gates plus explicit operator approval.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:17:Two target agents are supported with static profiles: `handover` (promotion-eligible) and `context-prime` (candidate-only). Each profile defines its own scoring rubric, fixture directory, aggregate score threshold, and repeatability tolerance. The benchmark runner (`run-benchmark.cjs`) scores fixture outputs against required headings, required patterns, and forbidden patterns.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:23:Canonical mutation requires a `candidate-better` score, passing benchmark report, repeatability evidence, manifest boundary compliance, and explicit approval. Rollback restores the archived pre-promotion backup and records a post-rollback comparison for audit continuity.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:43:The refactored `score-candidate.cjs` scores candidates across 5 weighted dimensions when invoked with `--dynamic`:
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:59:The refactored `reduce-state.cjs` tracks per-dimension scores across iterations, renders a Dimensional Progress table in the dashboard, and detects when all dimensions plateau (3+ identical scores) to trigger an automatic stop condition.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:73:The `@agent-improver` agent and `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` command are mirrored across all 5 runtimes (OpenCode, Claude, Codex, .agents, Gemini). The integration scanner checks mirror parity automatically.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:79:A 21-scenario testing playbook covers 6 categories: integration scanner, profile generator, 5D scorer, benchmark integration, reducer dimensions, and end-to-end loop. Each scenario has copy-pasteable commands and verification one-liners.
.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:85:Renamed from `sk-recursive-agent` to `deep-agent-improvement` across 187+ files and 1129+ occurrences. Command moved from `/speckit:recursive-agent` to `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`. Agent renamed from `@recursive-agent` to `@agent-improver`. Zero stale references remaining (verified by fresh sub-agent audit).
