    17	<!-- Keywords: deep-agent-improvement, deep-agent-improvement, agent-improvement, benchmark-harness, score-candidate, promote-candidate, rollback-candidate -->
    18	
    19	# Recursive Agent: Evaluator-First Improvement Orchestrator
    20	
    21	Evaluator-first workflow for testing whether a bounded agent surface can be improved without immediately mutating the source of truth. It combines packet-local candidates, deterministic scoring, repeatable benchmarks, and explicit promotion or rollback gates.
    22	
    23	---
    24	
    25	## 1. WHEN TO USE
    26	
    27	### Two Co-Equal Lanes
    28	
    29	This skill supports two co-equal use-case lanes that share the same candidate, dispatcher, and scorer seams:
    30	
    31	| Lane | Pick when | Command |
    32	| --- | --- | --- |
    33	| **Lane A: Agent-Improvement** | You want to improve a bounded agent `.md` file | `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` |
    34	| **Lane B: Model-Benchmark** | You want to benchmark a model or prompt framework | `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` |
    35	
    36	Lane A is detailed in §3 (Runtime Initialization, Proposal and Evaluation, Promotion and Recovery). Lane B is detailed in §4. Both lanes run the same loop shape and keep the agent-improvement path byte-identical when no mode flag is set.
    37	
    38	### Activation Triggers
    39	
    40	Use this skill when:
    41	- You want to test whether an agent prompt or instruction surface can be improved (Lane A)
    42	- You want to benchmark a model or prompt framework against repeatable fixtures (Lane B)
    43	- The mutation boundary is explicit and narrow
    44	- You need packet-local evidence instead of ad hoc prompt tweaking
    45	- You need target-specific benchmark or scoring rules before any canonical mutation
    46	- Promotion must stay gated behind independent evidence plus operator approval
    47	
    48	### Primary Use Cases
    49	
    50	#### Bounded Agent Improvement
    51	
    52	Use this skill to set up a proposal-first loop for any bounded agent file, write packet-local candidates, and record append-only evidence.
    53	
    54	#### Benchmark-Backed Evaluation
    55	
    56	Use this skill when candidate quality must be judged by produced artifacts and repeatability reports, not just by how a prompt file reads in isolation.
    57	
    58	#### Promotion and Rollback Verification
    59	
    60	Use this skill when you need to prove that guarded promotion, validation, rollback, and post-rollback comparison all work end to end without leaving hidden drift behind.
    61	
    62	#### Model and Prompt Benchmarking
    63	
    64	Use Lane B (model-benchmark) when the thing under test is a model or prompt framework rather than an agent definition. It runs the same loop shape against a benchmark profile and scores produced outputs, sharing the candidate, dispatcher, and scorer seams with the agent-improvement path. See §4 below.
    65	
    66	### When NOT to Use
    67	
    68	Do not use this skill for:
    69	- Open-ended prompt rewrites across multiple agent families at once
    70	- Direct canonical edits without a packet-local candidate and evaluator evidence
    71	- Broad runtime-mirror synchronization work presented as benchmark truth
    72	- General packet planning that belongs in `/speckit:plan` or implementation that does not need an improvement loop
    73	
    74	---
    75	
    76	## 2. SMART ROUTING
    77	
    78	
    79	### Resource Domains
    80	
    81	The router discovers markdown resources recursively from `references/` and `assets/`, then applies intent scoring so only the guidance that matches the current task is loaded.
    82	
    83	- `references/` for operator workflows, evaluator policy, promotion or rollback rules, target onboarding, and quick-reference guidance
    84	- `assets/` for reusable runtime templates such as the charter and strategy markdown files
    85	- `scripts/` for deterministic benchmark, scoring, reduction, promotion, rollback, and drift-check helpers
    86	
    87	**Lane awareness**: resources are organized by lane. `references/agent-improvement/` and `assets/agent-improvement/` carry Lane A guidance, while `references/model-benchmark/` and `assets/model-benchmark/` carry Lane B guidance. `RESOURCE_MAP` routes the `MODEL_BENCHMARK` intent to the Lane B references, and `RUNTIME_ASSETS` loads the Lane B benchmark profile only when the `MODEL_BENCHMARK` intent is selected. The `ALWAYS` and shared `references/shared/` resources apply to both lanes.
    88	
    89	### Resource Loading Levels
    90	
    91	| Level | When to Load | Resources |
    92	| --- | --- | --- |
    93	| ALWAYS | Every skill invocation | `references/shared/quick_reference.md` |
    94	| CONDITIONAL | If intent signals match | Workflow, policy, or onboarding references |
    95	| ON_DEMAND | Only on explicit request or full setup | Markdown runtime templates in `assets/` |
    96	
    97	### Smart Router Pseudocode
    98	
    99	The authoritative routing logic for scoped markdown loading and explicit runtime-asset loading.
   100	
   101	- Pattern 1: Runtime Discovery - `discover_markdown_resources()` recursively scans `references/` and `assets/`.
   102	- Pattern 2: Existence-Check Before Load - `load_if_available()` uses `_guard_in_skill()`, `inventory`, and `seen`.
   103	- Pattern 3: Extensible Routing Key - quick-reference, loop, evaluation, promotion, target onboarding, integration, and setup intents route resources.
   104	- Pattern 4: Multi-Tier Graceful Fallback - `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST` asks for target/action/gate disambiguation and missing intent routes return a "no knowledge base" notice.
   105	
   106	```python
   107	from pathlib import Path
   108	
   109	SKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent
   110	RESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / "references", SKILL_ROOT / "assets")
   111	DEFAULT_RESOURCE = "references/shared/quick_reference.md"
   112	
   113	INTENT_SIGNALS = {
   114	    "QUICK_REFERENCE": {"weight": 3, "keywords": ["quick reference", "short reminder", "command example"]},
   115	    "LOOP_EXECUTION": {"weight": 4, "keywords": ["run loop", "proposal", "candidate", "score candidate", "benchmark"]},
   116	    "EVALUATION_POLICY": {"weight": 4, "keywords": ["evaluator", "rubric", "contract", "repeatability", "no-go"]},
   117	    "PROMOTION_OPERATIONS": {"weight": 4, "keywords": ["promote", "rollback", "mirror drift", "approval gate"]},
   118	    "TARGET_ONBOARDING": {"weight": 4, "keywords": ["new target", "target profile", "onboarding", "second target"]},
   119	    "INTEGRATION_SCAN": {"weight": 4, "keywords": ["integration", "scan surfaces", "mirror sync", "dynamic profile", "5-dimension"]},
   120	    "MODEL_BENCHMARK": {"weight": 5, "keywords": ["benchmark a model", "benchmark a prompt framework", "optimize a model", "model-benchmark", "model benchmark"]},
   121	    "FULL_SETUP": {"weight": 3, "keywords": ["full setup", "initialize runtime", "charter", "strategy"]},
   122	}
   123	
   124	RESOURCE_MAP = {
   125	    "QUICK_REFERENCE": ["references/shared/quick_reference.md"],
   126	    "LOOP_EXECUTION": ["references/shared/loop_protocol.md", "references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md"],
   127	    "EVALUATION_POLICY": ["references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md", "references/shared/promotion_rules.md"],
   128	    "PROMOTION_OPERATIONS": ["references/shared/rollback_runbook.md", "references/agent-improvement/mirror_drift_policy.md", "references/shared/promotion_rules.md"],
   129	    "TARGET_ONBOARDING": ["references/agent-improvement/target_onboarding.md"],
   130	    "INTEGRATION_SCAN": ["references/agent-improvement/integration_scanning.md", "references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md"],
   131	    "MODEL_BENCHMARK": ["references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md", "references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md"],
   132	    "FULL_SETUP": ["assets/agent-improvement/improvement_charter.md", "assets/agent-improvement/improvement_strategy.md"],
   133	}
   134	
   135	RUNTIME_ASSETS = {
   136	    "ALWAYS": ["assets/agent-improvement/improvement_config.json", "assets/agent-improvement/target_manifest.jsonc"],
   137	    "MODEL_BENCHMARK": ["assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json"],
   138	}
   139	
   140	ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS = ["target profile", "score candidate", "proposal loop", "benchmark", "promotion gate", "mirror drift"]
   141	
   142	def _task_text(task) -> str:
   143	    return " ".join([
   144	        str(getattr(task, "text", "")),
   145	        str(getattr(task, "query", "")),
   146	        " ".join(getattr(task, "keywords", []) or []),
   147	    ]).lower()
   148	
   149	UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = ["Confirm target path", "Confirm proposal vs scoring vs promotion", "Confirm packet-local evidence path"]
   150	
   151	def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:
   152	    resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()
   153	    resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)
   154	    if resolved.suffix.lower() != ".md":
   155	        raise ValueError(f"Only markdown resources are routed here: {relative_path}")
   156	    return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()
   157	
   158	def discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:
   159	    docs = []
   160	    for base in RESOURCE_BASES:
   161	        if base.exists():
   162	            docs.extend(p for p in base.rglob("*.md") if p.is_file())
   163	    return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}
   164	
   165	def score_intents(task) -> dict[str, float]:
   166	    text = _task_text(task)
   167	    scores = {intent: 0.0 for intent in INTENT_SIGNALS}
   168	    for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():
   169	        for keyword in cfg["keywords"]:
   170	            if keyword in text:
   171	                scores[intent] += cfg["weight"]
   172	    return scores
   173	
   174	def select_intents(scores: dict[str, float], ambiguity_delta: float = 1.0, max_intents: int = 2) -> list[str]:
   175	    ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)
   176	    if not ranked or ranked[0][1] <= 0:
   177	        return ["QUICK_REFERENCE"]
   178	    selected = [ranked[0][0]]
   179	    if len(ranked) > 1 and ranked[1][1] > 0 and (ranked[0][1] - ranked[1][1]) <= ambiguity_delta:
   180	        selected.append(ranked[1][0])
   181	    return selected[:max_intents]
   182	
   183	def route_recursive_agent_resources(task):
   184	    inventory = discover_markdown_resources()
   185	    intents = select_intents(score_intents(task))
   186	    loaded = []
   187	    seen = set()
   188	
   189	    def load_if_available(relative_path: str) -> None:
   190	        guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)
   191	        if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:
   192	            load(guarded)
   193	            loaded.append(guarded)
   194	            seen.add(guarded)
   195	
   196	    load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)
   197	    for intent in intents:
   198	        for relative_path in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):
   199	            load_if_available(relative_path)
   200	
   201	    text = _task_text(task)
   202	    if any(keyword in text for keyword in ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS):
   203	        for paths in RESOURCE_MAP.values():
   204	            for relative_path in paths:
   205	                load_if_available(relative_path)
   206	
   207	    runtime_assets = list(RUNTIME_ASSETS["ALWAYS"])
   208	    if "MODEL_BENCHMARK" in intents:
   209	        runtime_assets.extend(RUNTIME_ASSETS.get("MODEL_BENCHMARK", []))
   210	
   211	    if not loaded:
   212	        load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)
   213	    return {"intents": intents, "resources": loaded, "runtime_assets": runtime_assets}
   214	```
   215	
   216	---
   217	
   218	## 3. LANE A: AGENT-IMPROVEMENT
   219	
   220	Lane A improves a bounded agent `.md` file. Command: `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`. It runs the proposal-first loop in three modes (initialization, proposal and evaluation, promotion and recovery) and scores candidates with dynamic-mode 5-dimension scoring.
   221	
   222	### Mode 1: Runtime Initialization
   223	
   224	1. Confirm the spec folder, target path, execution mode, and active target profile.
   225	2. Create `{spec_folder}/improvement/` plus the packet-local `candidates/`, `benchmark-runs/`, and `archive/` directories when needed.
   226	3. Copy in the runtime config, charter, strategy, and boundary templates.
   227	4. Record baseline state in the append-only ledger before the first candidate run.
   228	
   229	### Mode 2: Proposal and Evaluation
   230	
   231	1. Read the charter, boundary file, target profile, and canonical target surface.
   232	2. Run `scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs` to discover all surfaces the target agent touches.
   233	3. Write exactly one bounded candidate under the packet-local `candidates/` directory.
   234	4. Run `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs` to evaluate the candidate via dynamic-mode 5-dimension scoring (the sole supported path).
   235	5. Run `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs` to measure produced outputs against the active fixture set.
   236	6. Append score and benchmark results to the packet-local ledger.
   237	7. Run `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` to refresh the dashboard and experiment registry.
   238	
   239	### Mode 2A: Stress-Test Failure Paths Before Promotion Claims
   240	
   241	For changes that alter agent discipline, run at least one same-task A/B stress scenario before recommending promotion:
   242	
   243	1. Call A: a generic improvement attempt against an isolated sandbox copy of the target.
   244	2. Reset the sandbox to its baseline copy.
   245	3. Call B: the disciplined `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` path against the identical prompt and files.
   246	4. Judge only grep/file/diff/exit-code signals: helper invocation, packet-local candidate boundary, no canonical or mirror mutation before promotion, benchmark journal boundary, legal-stop gate keys, and stop-reason correctness.
   247	
   248	Do not treat `Read(SKILL.md)` or `skill(deep-agent-improvement)` as evidence that this protocol executed.
   249	
   250	### 5-Dimension Evaluation Framework
   251	
   252	Dynamic mode is the only scoring path. Scoring evaluates five dimensions:
   253	
   254	| Dimension | Weight | What It Measures |
   255	| --- | --- | --- |
   256	| Structural Integrity | 0.20 | Agent template compliance (required sections present) |
   257	| Rule Coherence | 0.25 | ALWAYS/NEVER rules align with workflow steps |
   258	| Integration Consistency | 0.25 | Mirrors in sync, commands reference agent, skills reference agent |
   259	| Output Quality | 0.15 | Output verification items present, no placeholder content |
   260	| System Fitness | 0.15 | Permission alignment, resource references valid, frontmatter complete |

